segments.text: You know, we have gone for federal funding for a lot of things.
And we have gotten some UDAG funds.
We have gotten some EDA funds.
We have gotten some urban transit funds, manpower programs.
public works projects that we have.
And we go on and on and on.
That includes drainage and flood control through the U.S. Board of Engineers.
Of course, the Federal Highway System.
So, yes, we are more involved with
the federal government .
The Settlement is 100% federal.
And there you had a direct relationship with, I guess, two presidents at that time, Kennedy and Johnson.
Nester, could you briefly describe how your department is organized, the basic structure of it?
Sure.
When I took over the department, we had the traditional hierarchy of organization.
We had the director, the assistant director, and we had eight or ten divisions.
We had subdivisions, zoning, transportation, relocation, graphics, cartography.
traditional system.
After my assistant director of planning retired Mr. Bill Adams in 1980, early 1983, I reorganized the office to change the whole pattern of it.
I felt that
the office should not have, or that it was rather impractical to have the director and the assistant director and then all of the subdivisions.
So I reorganized with a director and three division chiefs.
The three division chiefs, having to beat Joe Rubio, Judy Price, and Ned Kompis, all have under them several subdivisions that are grouped together by the nature of work that they do.
For example, Joe Rubio handles everything that has to do with
The plant commission has to do with now things, today things, subdivisions, zoning, site plan reviews, special permits.
Everything that has to do with the development aspects that is ongoing right now has to do with annexations that are ongoing.
So that is what is commonly known as current planning.
And I put Judy Price in charge of comprehensive planning and transportation, transportation and .
She actually wears three hats.
She is the chief of comprehensive planning, she is the MPO for the city, and she is the
person in charge of the major thoroughfare plan or all thoroughfare planning in the city.
So she has under her wing demographics, she has encompassed planning and everything that has to do with transportation including doing the grants for the
public transit system.
Then I have the third, which is Ned Comfort, who is in charge of urban design.
And urban design is involved with graphics, cryptography, design plans that are ongoing today.
such as downtown revitalization, such as neighborhood revitalization, such as doing neighborhood commercial and housing programs.
He's also in charge of relocation, which goes very well with this.
So that's basically how I have it set up.
The neat thing about this particular program that I have is that
I took the assistant director position and divided its powers into the three and promoted the three.
And they are not only supervisory in nature, but they are also working technicians, working professionals that realize that they are not only in charge of their division,
But they are also required to produce work instead of being the overseer, which generally an assistant director, that's what he does.
You talk to your assistant, and your assistant then turns around and assigns and sees that things get done.
But in very few instances do you have an assistant director of any department feel that, aside from general supervision, that he is not expected to do it.
One question that I want to be sure to ask you is, taking a look into the future, what
future direction do you see for El Paso's planning?
Are there any changes in the wind?
Or any changes that you feel are most likely to occur?
First of all, I have a very strong feeling that we are very, very short-handed manpower.
How many staff do you have?
I have approximately 36 right now, 35 or 36.
And out of that, how many would you classify as professional planners?
Give or take 12.
I mean, truly professional planners in various processes, for comp planning or subdivisions and that sort of thing.
My biggest complaint is that the city of El Paso is growing.
We're half a million people.
We are extremely tight in terms of personnel.
We have lost some very key people in the past several months.
And there is no help in sight that I can see to request additional personnel.
As I mentioned to you in the beginning, back in the 60s, we enjoyed some excellent manning tables for the department.
We had more help than we needed.
Consequently, we used to carry two or three vacant positions from year to year.
Planner twos and planner threes, which is, you know, top of the line.
And nobody really cared whether you would carry these vacant positions from year to year.
You'd say, well, yeah, I've got two or three positions vacant, but I won't fill them next year.
Today, it is...
It is just, you know, if you have a vacant position and you go to the budget, you're going to lose it.
It's going to be wiped out.
To get another body in the department is going to be extremely difficult.
So what I'm really saying is as the city grows bigger and bigger, we're getting skimpier and skimpier, and that is the biggest challenge
challenge, problem, the planning problem is facing right now.
That's number one.
By not fulfilling the overall mission of planning, it is entirely possible that we could lose some clout with the mayor and council.
You know, you can just do so much with what you have and you're going to from time to time become, you're going to slip or you're going to not do the job that you would like to do.
Consequently, your image, credibility, this political position in the organization may
They get hurt.
That's a fear.
Because historically here, planning has played a major role in local government.
And it would be a shame if now through personnel shortages and so forth, that were to change.
That's a possibility.
There's also a...
danger that the Public Works Office may be gaining political clout and may position to hurt the Department of Planning.
That's my personal observation.
There always seems to be kind of a historic rivalry between the two departments in every city, subtle or overt.
Sure.
And it's just natural because of all the departments, we seem to be able to understand a more comprehensive view of the city.
It probably works.
kind of six or eight major departments under his belt, like streets, sanitation, traffic and transportation, engineering, public works.
There's another one in there.
So you're talking about what is generally classified as a super department.
And so there's obviously more
interest or there's more interplay between that and the middle council than a pure, simple department.
I'm going to have to leave, too.
I got to go.
Aside from the personnel and the possible
diminution of, as it were, clout in the city.
Do you see any other changes in the future planning in El Paso?
The type of planning or the way you spend your resources?
Not really.
I think the biggest challenge of your contact is to keep up with

development changes where we are, you know, in rhythm with the rest of the country in terms of innovative ways of doing things such as performance standards, for one, or performance zoning, new PODs, new residential developments requiring flexibility as opposed to the traditional zoning districts.
I think we need to keep an open mind without hindering quality.
For instance, the big issue of narrower streets, where you don't need bigger streets, a hierarchical streets program, smaller lots, higher densities.
changing patterns of community development, which is our business.
What I'm saying is I'm hoping that we can at least keep an open mind and be able to stay up with current events.
The other issue is to get fully computerized.
We are promised that this year we will be computerized in plenty.
We've been fighting for computerization for the last two years.
Things work slow, but I think we will be able to persuade the Mayor and Council to do something.
We're very close to obeying that.
Minister, thank you very much.
I appreciate it.
He was tired, I think, yes.
Well, he's always tired, what a job.
Tired, tired, you're always tired.
Now let's see if this is recording.
This is March 15th, 1985, and we are in the kitchen of Mrs. Jonathan Cunningham, otherwise known as Ann.
And Mrs. Cunningham followed the career of her husband quite closely.
And Ann, I want to ask you, would you recall how it was that you and Jonathan first met?
And then take it from there to the early years of his career, and then all of that, and then how it came to be that you located in El Paso.
Yes.
I recall well that we met as graduate students at the University of Chicago.
We attended lectures together.
In fact, one man I distinctly remember, Rexford Tugwell, gave a fine planning lecture about his work in Puerto Rico.
Jonathan and I shared many happy memories of the University of Chicago, where he
was LD White's administrative assistant and instructor in one of his many fine classes in public administration.
Then John's role in World War II was with the military intelligence.
He did a great deal of mapping.

for the Air Transport Command in the South Pacific, received the Bronze Star Medal for his research and writing about air routes that could be used with efficiency and with great finesse, let's say, to bring troops and supplies.
to the South Pacific during World War II.
After the war, Jonathan went back to the University of Chicago and was an all but dissertation person in the field of public administration.
Then his first professional job after the war was at Whitman College, where he taught political science.
public administration, was indeed chairman of the political science department there.
And at the same time, he assumed the duties of planning director for the little village of Walla Walla and did write their planning and zoning ordinance for them.
Within a few years, he became so attracted to planning that he moved to Spokane, Washington, where he was director of county planning for about two

three years and then we moved on to Olympia Washington where John became the first regional planner of the Puget Sound area and formed the Puget Sound Regional Planning Council one of the first regional planning councils in the United States as I remember
We came to El Paso because John was essentially a Southwestern-er, basically, spiritually, in every way a Southwestern-er.
He had a fine boyhood and youth in New Mexico and was attracted to the region always.
When Mayor Raymond Telles invited him to be a planning director,
Do you remember how Teas spelled his last name?
T-E-L-L-E-S, Teas.
When Teas invited Jonathan to be planning director, he was honored and sacrificed a good career in the Northwest and a bit of salary to come down and be planning director for the city of El Paso.
And he delighted in the new challenge.
It was indeed a challenge.
And he, I can honestly say, really
really loved his work in El Paso because it did demand the best of him.
And he continually felt that because he knew the region, he could contribute a great deal to the planning efforts for this community.
Well, John seemed to know how to relate to the people here in the Southwest, to all sorts of people.
poor, rich, powerful, not so powerful, and he understood them.
He was a people planner.
And although he was not bilingual, he had many friends in Mexico and in Juarez.
And he was liked by the Mexican-American population in El Paso very much.
He was invited to their LULAC functions.
He was invited to teach at the university in Juarez.
They provided him with an interpreter, translator, excuse me.
And he taught a course in city planning administration at UT El Paso and found time generally to serve the universities in the area.
He also gave freely of his time and speaking ability to New Mexico State University.
So he had a fine time here as a planner and as a professional teacher.
Essentially, he conceived the idea

of a fine city planner as also being a teacher because he felt that people needed to be educated as to what the real role of city planning was and what it could do for a community and what it ought to be thinking of doing and what its goal should be.
So he made city planning not only a career, but he made it a teaching dedication.
And on that, that reminds me of when I first met Jonathan in 1970 at the San Antonio conference of the Gulf Southwest chapter of AIP.
I had just been authorized by the then president, Vernon Henry, to proceed with the development of a short course for planning commissioners.
And Jonathan was one of the first supporters of such a move on the part of the chapter, because he did believe in education of planning commissioners and the general public.

So he was on the original task force for the short course for planning commissioners, which, of course, now has evolved into the Educational Foundation, which is separately incorporated and is one of the
probably one of the best activities that the chapter has to its credit.
And it received a National Honor Award for the development of this short course.
I'm glad to hear that, because he did feel it was extremely important.
Now, I consider the acquisition of the Chamizal National Park one of Jonathan's great achievements for El Paso.
He had good contacts in the Department of the Interior.
And when he found out that there was to be a transfer of land between the two countries, Jonathan conceived the idea that land should be set aside within the city of El Paso for a national park.
And he did indeed pursue that vigorously in Washington and did effectuate the
idea and promote it and did get it for the city and it's still much used.
It's a cultural center for the city.
The administrator Frank Smith and John were good friends and Frank often tells me that if it were not for John that we would not have the Shamizel National Park there and it would not be such a
a great inspiration to this community, which does need a great deal of cultural inspiration.
Okay.

Well, looking back on planning in El Paso since you've been here, several things have happened in addition to the Chamazul Park and the redefinition of the international boundary between Mexico and Texas.
I think you mentioned previously that there was a series of neighborhood parks that were promoted as a policy by John?
Yes.
He loved the city of Spokane because it had so many wonderful city parks.
In fact, I believe Spokane, Washington is still noted for its numerous park plans and developments.
When Jonathan came to El Paso, he did note immediately the few parks in the area.
And this was one of his dedications to acquire and to develop more parkland for the city.
And he was especially instrumental in getting the Armijo Park
recreational center developed, which is used constantly in South El Paso.
He promoted the idea with the park department director that we should have more parks, and he worked continuously with him.
to acquire more parks for the city of El Paso.
And although we haven't as many as Spokane, we do have our fair share and they are well located in every section of the city now.
I know that he was an advocate of George Kessler's planning and caused an abstract of Kessler's 1925 plan for El Paso to be reprinted.
and distributed on the occasion of its anniversary.
And as such, he also advocated comprehensive planning and made sure that El Paso moved constantly in that direction rather than in the direction of the currently more popular type of policy plans.
Would you like to comment on that?

I know that whenever he had a chance, whenever he had people who could write that he could depend upon on his staff, he tried to update the plan for El Paso and worked so hard to do that and to get a consensus of view and approval for his plans.
Each year he published

report too from the city planning department of the achievements of the past year and noted what had been done with maps and illustrations so that anyone wishing to keep track of the city planning department and know what how the city was growing and what planning was being done could consult those publications he was very proud of the
publications that came out of his office and they were well done, well written, and beautifully printed.
I think it would be a good idea to be able to use excerpts of some of those in the book.
Yes.
Yes, my daughter and I are planning to catalog the publications we have and they are numerous.

Jonathan was with the department for 20 years and he did publish and I'm sorry that he's perished but some of his ideas live on and he's still well thought of in the community and many do speak to me and tell me that they appreciated his efforts on behalf of this city.
El Paso doesn't have a city manager.
And I heard it said some years ago that the nearest thing that El Paso had to a city manager was Jonathan, because he considered planning to be so important with respect to the political arena.
And he kept close to it and kept the mayor and the council informed
and more or less served as the planning arm of the city council and the mayor, particularly the mayor.
Well, his concept of what the city needed here was, I believe, an interdepartmental communication route of ideas.
And he did set up, as I recall,

meetings for the department heads of the city to discuss and promote and inform each other of what they were doing so that there was never a lack of communication between department heads of the procedures in various departments.
And this, I understand, was helpful.
No, Jonathan really was not.
a city manager in essence he was an understated person many times with his equals and superiors he was looked to for advice by as you pointed out businessmen and men who were just beginning to
develop as leaders in this community.
